<li><p>On average, a gallon of paint covers 350 square feet. Will you have enough paint if you buy one quart?</p></li>
</ol></p></activity>

<p>When we calculate the sum of the areas of the outside faces of a three-dimensional object, it is called the <term>surface area</term> of the object. The simplest object for finding surface area is a box. Here is one.</p>
      <image source="box1.png" width="45%"></image>

<example><statement><p>Find the surface area of the box shown above. The dimensions are given in meters.</p></statement>

<solution><p>The box has six faces: front and back, top and bottom, left and right. Here are the areas of the six faces.</p>

  <p>Front:  <m>6 \times 3 = 18</m>  square meters</p>
  <p>Back: same as the front</p>
  <p>Top:  <m>6 \times 4 = 24</m>  square meters</p>
  <p>Bottom: same as the top</p>
  <p>Right:  <m>4 \times 3 = 12</m>  square meters</p>
  <p>Left: same as the right</p>

  <p>Finally, we add the areas of the six faces.
      <me>18 + 18 + 24 + 24 + 12 + 12 = 108~~ \text{square meters}</me></p></solution></example>

<note><p>You may find it easier to visualize the six faces of the box in an "unfolded" diagram.</p>
    <image source="cutbox.png" width="40%"></image>
<p>Imagine cutting the edges of the box on the red lines above and unfolding it to get a flat surface that looks like this:</p>
    <image source="unfoldedbox.png" width="50%"></image>
<p>If you fold up the sides along the yellow lines and close the top, you will get back the original box. (You can try this yourself by tracing the figure onto a piece of paper and cutting it out!)</p></note>
</subsection>

<subsection><title>Boxes and Cubes</title>

<p>A <term>cube</term> is a box whose length, width, and height are all equal. That means that all six faces are identical. Here is a cube and an unfolded version.</p>
    <image source="cube.png" width="70%"></image>

<exercise><statement><p>A wooden block in the shape of a cube measures 3 inches on each side. What is its surface area?</p></statement>

<answer><p>54 sq in</p></answer></exercise>

