<subsection><title>Volume</title>

<p>Remember the cube in Exercise 1? In that exercise we were interested in the outer surface of the cube, the six faces that can be "unfolded" into a flat two-dimensional surface. Now we'll switch our focus to the three-dimensional space enclosed inside a box. We'll use cubes to measure that space.</p>
  
<p>Just as we use square units, such as square inches or square meters, to measure the area of a two-dimensional region, we use <term>cubic units</term> to measure the <term>volume</term> or amount of space inside a three-dimensional object. For instance, a <term>cubic inch</term> is the
 amount of space enclosed inside a cube that measures 1 inch on each side. A <term>cubic meter</term> is ....  well, you get the idea.</p>
    <image source="areavolume.png" width="90%"></image>

<example><statement><p>Find the volume of the box shown below. The grid lines represent centimeters.</p>
    <image source="boxvol.png" width="40%"></image></statement>

<solution><p>We'd like to know how many "blocks," or cubic centimeters fit inside the box. Do we have to count them all? No:  first let's look at just the top layer of blocks.</p>
      <image source="boxlayer.png" width="50%"></image>
<p>Counting along the front face, there are 6 rows of 4 blocks each. So the volume of the top layer is
    <me>6 \times 4 = 24~~\text{cubic centimeters}</me>
Now, there are 3 layers of blocks, each containing 24 blocks, so the total number of blocks is
    <me>3 \times 24 = 72~~\text{cubic centimeters}</me>
The volume of the box is 72 cubic centimeters.</p>
</solution></example>

<note><p>We don't really need the grid lines to help us calculate the volume of a box. For example, here is a picture of a box with the standard labels for its dimensions.</p>
    <image source="dimensionsbox.png" width="45%"></image>
<p>Let's look at a particular example. We'll figure out how many cubic inches fit inside the box below, just as we did in Example 2.</p>
    <image source="vol2400box.png" width="60%"></image>
<p>The box is 10 inches high, so there are 10 layers of cubic inch blocks. Each layer contains 20 rows of 12 blocks each. One layer contains
    <me>20 \times 12 = 240 \hphantom{0} \text{cubic inches}</me>
There are 10 layers of 240 blocks, for a total of
    <me>10 \times 240 = 2400 \hphantom{0} \text{cubic inches}</me>
The volume of the box is 2400 cubic inches.</p></note>

<exercise><statement><p><ol marker="a">
    <li><p>Draw a box, and label it with these dimensions:</p>
        <p>length = 3 feet,  width = 5 feet,  height = 8 feet</p></li>
    <li><p>Find the volume of the box.</p></li>
    <li><p>Do you see an easy way to find the volume of a box when you know its dimensions? Describe your method.</p></li>
  </ol></p></statement>
  
  <answer><p><ol marker="a">
    <li><image xml:id="box-3by5by8" width="22%" margins="0% 78%"><description>box 3 by 5 by 8</description><latex-image>
        <![CDATA[
        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=.4]
        \draw[gray, thick, dashed] (2,2) rectangle ++(3,8);
        \draw[gray, thick, dashed] (0,0) --++(2,2);
        \draw[thick] (0,0) rectangle (3,8);
        \draw[thick](3,8)--++(2,2);
        \draw[thick](3,0)--++(2,2)--++(0,8)--++(-3,0)--++(-2,-2);
        \node[text width=1cm, text=blue] at (2.4,-.6){3 ft};
        \node[text width=1cm, text=blue] at (5.5,.5){5 ft};
        \node[text width=1cm, text=blue] at (7,5){8 ft};
        \end{tikzpicture}]]>
        </latex-image></image></li>
    <li><p>120 cu ft</p></li>
    <li><p>Multiply the length times the width times the height.</p></li>
  </ol></p></answer></exercise>
  
